 THE 2026 REALITY THAT CHANGES EVERYTHING
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

  AI Overviews appear on 50-60% of all US searches (up from 6% in Jan 2025)
  65-69% of Google searches end WITHOUT a click (zero-click era)
  Organic CTR drops 61% when AI Overview is present

  BUT: Pages CITED inside AI Overviews earn +35% organic clicks + 91% more paid clicks
  AND: AI-driven visitors convert at 4.4x the rate of standard organic visitors
  AND: 46.5% of AI Overview citations come from pages ranked OUTSIDE top 50

  THE SHIFT: Ranking position matters less. Citation readiness matters more.
  THE GOAL: Every blixamo article must pass the EXTRACTION TEST (Rule 29)

  Citation source breakdown:
  - 44% of citations from first 30% of text
  - FAQ sections nearly DOUBLE ChatGPT citation probability
  - Semantic completeness r=0.87 (strongest predictor of AI citation)

═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
 BAYESIAN ARTICLE FRAMEWORK
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

  PRIOR    -> Google keyword. What format/length/angle do top 3 show?
  EVIDENCE -> Ankit's real, first-hand, production experience?
  POSTERIOR -> Format + depth + angle that maximizes P(rank) x P(citation)?
  ACTION   -> Write to beat #1 on Google AND get extracted by AI Overview

  P(rank) multipliers:
  Indian-specific keyword         +20%
  Ankit personally used the tool  +25%
  Original data (real numbers)    +20%
  Stat/citation every 150-200w    +30% AI citation
  Generic roundup (no real use)   -30%
  Under 800 words                 -40%
  No internal links               -25%

  3 mandatory pre-write checks:
  1. Google keyword -> what format/schema dominates?
  2. Check AI Overview -> what does it cite?
  3. Ankit has real experience? -> if NO, pick different article

═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
 THE 34 RULES
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

RULE 1 — FRONTMATTER (17 fields, zero placeholders)
  title, slug, description (150-160 chars), date, updatedAt, author,
  category, tags (6-10), keyword, secondaryKeywords (4), featured,
  featuredImage, schema, difficulty, timeToComplete, excerpt, toc

  Title formulas:
    Tutorial:   "How to [Keyword] in 2026 (Step-by-Step)"
    Comparison: "[A] vs [B] in 2026 — [Honest verdict]"
    Listicle:   "[N] Best [Keyword] for Indian Developers in 2026"
    Review:     "[Tool] Review 2026: [Verdict in 4 words]"

  META DESCRIPTION RULES (description field):
  — Exactly 150-160 characters. Not shorter. Not longer.
  — Must include at least one: specific number, ₹ price, or measurable outcome
  — Must create curiosity OR urgency — reader must feel they will miss something
  — Match keyword intent: informational vs comparison vs tool recommendation
  — Write as Ankit — Indian indie dev who tested this. Not corporate.
  — BANNED openers: "Learn how to", "In this article", "This guide covers"
  — Comparison articles: hint at a clear winner WITHOUT revealing it
  — Tool/listicle articles: lead with ₹ price (Free / ₹465/month) as hook
  — Tutorial articles: mention time saved or exact problem solved

  META DESCRIPTION EXAMPLES:
    BAD:  "Coolify and Caprover are two open-source platforms. Learn which is right."
    GOOD: "Ran both on a ₹465/month Hetzner VPS for 30 days. One failed under load.
           Here's what actually happened and which one I'd deploy again."

    BAD:  "A list of the best PostgreSQL GUI tools available in 2026."
    GOOD: "Tested 7 free PostgreSQL GUI tools on a live Hetzner VPS. 3 were too slow
           for remote DBs. The 4 that actually work — including one that opens in 2s."

  VERIFY char count before saving:
    echo -n "your description here" | wc -c  → must output 150-160

RULE 2 — KEYWORD PLACEMENT
  Title: keyword first 5 words | Slug: exact keyword | First 100 words: once
  First H2: keyword or variant | Meta: keyword first 10 words
  Density: 1-2% | NEVER stuff, max 4-5 exact matches

RULE 3 — TARGET LENGTH (NON-NEGOTIABLE)
  Type              MIN      TARGET   MAX
  Tutorial/How-to   1,500w   2,500w   3,000w
  Comparison/vs     1,800w   3,500w   4,500w
  Listicle          2,000w   3,500w   4,500w
  Pillar page       3,500w   6,000w   8,000w
  Tool review       1,500w   2,500w   3,000w
  FAQ/explainer     1,200w   2,000w   2,500w

  Each H2 section: 350-450 words. One SCU per H2. One stat per 150-200 words.

  ENFORCEMENT — Claude MUST follow before finishing any article:
  1. Count words after first draft
  2. If BELOW minimum -> expand:
     a. Add more steps to Troubleshooting H2
     b. Expand FAQ answers to full 180 words each
     c. Add "Why this matters" after each major step
     d. Add Prerequisites + environment context section
     e. Add real example/output after each command block
  3. If ABOVE maximum -> trim:
     a. Cut repeated points across sections
     b. Shorten intro agitate/promise to 2 sentences each
     c. Remove steps obvious to the target reader
  4. NEVER pad with filler sentences to hit word count
  5. NEVER truncate mid-topic to stay under maximum
  6. Check word count BEFORE writing frontmatter

RULE 4 — CONTENT STRUCTURE (exact sequence)
  INTRO ZONE (first 30%):
    1. HOOK (Rule 5)
    2. AGITATE
    3. PROMISE
    4. PROOF
    5. TL;DR BOX — <Callout type="info" title="TL;DR">
    6. PREREQUISITES (Rule 32) — tutorials only
    7. QUICK TABLE (comparisons only)

  BODY ZONE (middle 40%):
    8. CONTEXT H2
    9. MAIN H2s with SCU blocks (Rule 26)
    10. DECISION H2 (comparisons only)

  CLOSE ZONE (final 30%):
    11. TROUBLESHOOT H2
    12. FULL TABLE (comparisons only)
    13. FAQ H2 (Rule 7)
    14. WHAT NEXT CTA (Rule 14)

RULE 5 — HOOK FORMAT
  BANNED: "In this article...", "Are you looking for...", "Have you ever wondered..."
  REQUIRED: "I [did the actual thing] — [outcome that creates tension]."
  Must pass: first-person + real number + curiosity/tension + under 30 words

RULE 6 — H2/H3 STRUCTURE
  H2: one per 300-400 words, 6-10 total, 350-450 words per section
  Troubleshooting H2 mandatory. FAQ H2 mandatory.
  H3: FAQ questions ALWAYS as H3 (not bold), 120-180 words each

RULE 7 — FAQ (HIGHEST IMPACT)
  6-8 questions minimum. H3 tags only (NOT **bold**).
  Exact Google PAA match questions. 60-180 word SCU answers.
  Start answer with direct answer in sentence 1.

  SCHEMA BUG: extractFAQs() only parses ### H3.
  **bold** questions = ZERO JSON-LD output, silently.
  CORRECT:  ### Does Hetzner accept Indian debit cards?
  BROKEN:   **Does Hetzner accept Indian debit cards?**
  Run: grep -A2 "Frequently Asked" article.mdx | grep "^\*\*" -> must return EMPTY

RULE 8 — INTERNAL LINKS
  3-5 per article. 1 in first 500 words. Bidirectional.
  BANNED anchors: "click here", "read more", "here"

  LIVE INDEX:
  pay-hetzner-from-india | multiple-projects-single-vps |
  deploy-nextjs-coolify-hetzner | indian-debit-cards-dev-tools |
  coolify-vs-caprover-2026 | whatsapp-ai-assistant-n8n-claude-api |
  nextjs-mdx-blog-2026 | free-tools-indian-indie-developer

RULE 9 — E-E-A-T (4+ signals)
  [ ] Real numbers (RAM, cost Rs+EUR, time, versions)
  [ ] Personal outcome statement
  [ ] Failure story + exact reason
  [ ] Version specificity ("Next.js 15.5.12", "Ubuntu 24.04")
  [ ] Freshness signal in first 200 words
  [ ] Cost breakdown EUR+INR
  [ ] Production proof
  [ ] Real timed comparison

RULE 10 — IMAGES (COMPLETE SYSTEM v8)

  WHY IMAGES MATTER — THE RESEARCH BEHIND THESE RULES
  ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
  These rules are not aesthetic preferences. They come from data:

  67% task completion boost (TechSmith)
  → Readers following tutorials complete them 67% more often with images.
  → RULE: Every bash/code block in a tutorial gets a real screenshot after it.
  → An article with 8 code blocks and 0 screenshots loses ~67% of readers mid-article.

  13ms brain processing (MIT)
  → Reader forms impression of page before reading a single word.
  → Image 1 IS the pitch — it signals "real guide" or "AI slop".
  → RULE: Image 1 always lands after TL;DR, before first H2. No exceptions.
  → A real terminal screenshot in position 1 = lower bounce than any illustration.

  Image type hierarchy (Josh Comeau, Smashing, CSS-Tricks)
  → Custom dark illustrations > annotated screenshots > data charts > generic images
  → RULE: Use this order when choosing what to make. Dark custom card > screenshot > chart.
  → Exception: real screenshots beat all for tutorials (authenticity > aesthetics).

  Ideogram 3.0 text accuracy: 95% vs Midjourney 40% (benchmark data)
  → Any image containing ₹ prices, tool names, numbers = use Ideogram only.
  → RULE: Midjourney for pure visual concepts. Ideogram for anything with text/numbers.
  → Using Midjourney for cost charts wastes 3-4 regenerations on broken text.

  Comparison/vs + listicles = most shareable format (content marketing data)
  → These articles get tweeted because they validate reader's own choices.
  → RULE: Every comparison and listicle must have 1 STANDALONE shareable image —
    a verdict card or cost bar chart that makes sense without reading the article.
  → This image serves double duty: in-article Image 1 + tweet attachment.

